<h2>Error Recovery</h2>
<p>
    Technical implementation of the <a href="/intents/reliability/">Reliability Intent</a>, handling retry strategies
    (exponential backoff, linear, immediate), HTTP status classification, circuit breaker patterns, and offline queuing.
    The complement to <a href="/blocks/resource-loader/">Resource Loader</a>'s error state &mdash; Error Recovery decides
    <strong>what happens next</strong> when a load fails.
    Part of the <a href="/projects/webresources/">Web Resources</a> ecosystem.
</p>

<h3>Architecture: Error Recovery in the Resource Pipeline</h3>
<p>
    <a href="/blocks/resource-loader/">Resource Loader</a> transitions to the <code>error</code> state when a fetch fails.
    Error Recovery intercepts this transition and applies recovery strategies before the error surfaces to the user.
    It sits between the transport layer (<a href="/resources/clients/">Custom Clients</a>) and the UI layer (Resource Loader),
    deciding whether to retry, queue, or surface the error.
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th></th><th>Resource Loader</th><th>Error Recovery</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Responsibility</strong></td>
            <td>Display loading states and content</td>
            <td>Decide recovery strategy on failure</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>When active</strong></td>
            <td>Always (idle → loading → success/error)</td>
            <td>Only on failure (error state entry)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>UX output</strong></td>
            <td>Skeleton, overlay, stale content</td>
            <td>Retry button, fallback content, queued indicator</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Configured by</strong></td>
            <td><a href="/intents/loader/">Loader Intent</a></td>
            <td><a href="/intents/reliability/">Reliability Intent</a></td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

