<h3>HTTP Status Classification</h3>
<p>
    Error Recovery classifies HTTP responses into three categories that determine the recovery path.
    The <code>Retry-After</code> header, when present, always overrides the configured backoff timing.
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Category</th><th>Status Codes</th><th>Recovery Behavior</th><th>Rationale</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Terminal</strong></td>
            <td>400, 401, 403, 404, 405, 409, 422</td>
            <td>No retry. Surface error immediately.</td>
            <td>Client errors &mdash; retrying with the same request will produce the same result.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Retryable</strong></td>
            <td>500, 502, 503, 504</td>
            <td>Automatic retry with configured backoff strategy.</td>
            <td>Server errors &mdash; transient failures that may resolve on retry.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Rate Limited</strong></td>
            <td>429</td>
            <td>Retry after <code>Retry-After</code> header delay (or fallback to exponential).</td>
            <td>Server explicitly asks to slow down. Respecting the header is both polite and effective.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Offline</strong></td>
            <td><code>navigator.onLine === false</code></td>
            <td>Queue operation. Retry when <code>online</code> event fires.</td>
            <td>No network &mdash; retrying immediately is wasteful. Queue and wait for connectivity.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Retry Strategies</h3>
<p>
    Three backoff algorithms are available. The Reliability Intent selects <code>automatic</code> recovery;
    Error Recovery decides the backoff curve based on the failure category.
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Formula</th><th>Example (base = 1s)</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Immediate</strong></td>
            <td><code>delay = 0</code></td>
            <td>0ms, 0ms, 0ms</td>
            <td>Idempotent reads where the failure is likely a one-off glitch</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Linear</strong></td>
            <td><code>delay = base × attempt</code></td>
            <td>1s, 2s, 3s</td>
            <td>Moderate backoff when server is likely recovering</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Exponential</strong></td>
            <td><code>delay = base × 2^(attempt-1) + jitter</code></td>
            <td>1s, 2s, 4s (+ random 0-500ms)</td>
            <td>Server overload scenarios; jitter prevents thundering herd</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Circuit Breaker</h3>
<p>
    After repeated failures to the same endpoint, Error Recovery can trip a circuit breaker to prevent
    wasted requests. This protects both the server (reduces load during outage) and the user (fast failure
    instead of waiting for timeout).
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>State</th><th>Behavior</th><th>Transition</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><code>closed</code></td>
            <td>Requests flow normally. Failure counter increments on error.</td>
            <td>→ <code>open</code> when failure count ≥ threshold</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>open</code></td>
            <td>Requests fail immediately without hitting the network. Fires <code>resource-circuit-open</code>.</td>
            <td>→ <code>half-open</code> after cooldown period expires</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>half-open</code></td>
            <td>A single probe request is allowed through.</td>
            <td>→ <code>closed</code> on success; → <code>open</code> on failure</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Offline Queuing</h3>
<p>
    When <code>navigator.onLine</code> is <code>false</code>, Error Recovery queues failed operations
    instead of retrying. When the <code>online</code> event fires on <code>window</code>, queued operations
    are replayed in order.
</p>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Detect</strong> &mdash; <code>navigator.onLine === false</code> or fetch throws <code>TypeError</code> (network error).</li>
    <li><strong>Queue</strong> &mdash; Operation stored in memory (or IndexedDB for persistence). Fires <code>resource-offline-queued</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Wait</strong> &mdash; Listen for <code>window.addEventListener('online', replay)</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Replay</strong> &mdash; On connectivity restored, queued operations are replayed sequentially with fresh AbortSignals.</li>
</ol>
<p>
    <strong>Progressive Enhancement:</strong> If a Service Worker is registered with the
    <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Background_Synchronization_API">Background Sync API</a>,
    Error Recovery delegates queued operations to the SW for more reliable replay (survives page close).
</p>

<h3>Usage Examples</h3>

<h4>Automatic Retry with Exponential Backoff</h4>
{% highlight "html" %}
<resource-loader resource="users"
    reliability-recovery="automatic"
    reliability-strategy="exponential"
    reliability-max-retries="3">
    <!-- Content renders on success -->
</resource-loader>
{% endhighlight %}

<h4>Manual Retry with Fallback</h4>
{% highlight "html" %}
<resource-loader resource="dashboard"
    reliability-recovery="manual"
    reliability-fallback="previous">
    <!-- On error: shows stale data + "Retry" button -->
</resource-loader>
{% endhighlight %}

<h4>Programmatic Configuration</h4>
{% highlight "typescript" %}
// Configure retry behavior via injector
docInjector.set('customContexts:errorRecovery', {
  strategy: 'exponential',
  maxRetries: 3,
  baseDelay: 1000,       // 1 second
  maxDelay: 30000,       // 30 second cap
  jitter: true,          // Random 0–500ms added
  circuitBreaker: {
    threshold: 5,        // Open after 5 consecutive failures
    cooldown: 60000      // Try again after 60 seconds
  },
  respectRetryAfter: true,
  classifyStatus: (status) => {
    if (status === 429) return 'rate-limited';
    if (status >= 400 && status < 500) return 'terminal';
    if (status >= 500) return 'retryable';
    return 'terminal';
  }
});
{% endhighlight %}

<h3>Events</h3>
<p>
    Error Recovery dispatches typed event classes registered via <a href="/projects/webevents/">Web Events</a> provider keys.
    The <code>resource-retry</code> event is cancelable &mdash; canceling it aborts the entire retry sequence.
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Event</th><th>Class</th><th>Provider Key</th><th>Detail</th><th>Cancelable</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><code>resource-retry</code></td>
            <td><code>ResourceRetryEvent</code></td>
            <td><code>customEvents:resource-retry</code></td>
            <td><code>{ attempt, maxAttempts, delay, error }</code></td>
            <td>Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>resource-retry-exhausted</code></td>
            <td><code>ResourceRetryExhaustedEvent</code></td>
            <td><code>customEvents:resource-retry-exhausted</code></td>
            <td><code>{ attempts, lastError, strategy }</code></td>
            <td>No</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>resource-offline-queued</code></td>
            <td><code>ResourceOfflineQueuedEvent</code></td>
            <td><code>customEvents:resource-offline-queued</code></td>
            <td><code>{ operation, queueSize }</code></td>
            <td>No</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>resource-circuit-open</code></td>
            <td><code>ResourceCircuitOpenEvent</code></td>
            <td><code>customEvents:resource-circuit-open</code></td>
            <td><code>{ failures, threshold, cooldown }</code></td>
            <td>No</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Interface</h3>
<pre><code class="language-typescript">/** Retry strategy configuration */
interface RetryStrategy {
    algorithm: 'immediate' | 'linear' | 'exponential';
    maxRetries: number;         // Default: 3
    baseDelay: number;          // ms, default: 1000
    maxDelay: number;           // ms cap, default: 30000
    jitter: boolean;            // Add random delay to prevent thundering herd
    respectRetryAfter: boolean; // Honor Retry-After header
}

/** Circuit breaker configuration */
interface CircuitBreakerConfig {
    threshold: number;   // Failures before opening (default: 5)
    cooldown: number;    // ms before half-open probe (default: 60000)
}

/** Circuit breaker runtime state */
type CircuitBreakerState = 'closed' | 'open' | 'half-open';

/** HTTP status classification */
type StatusClassification =
    | 'terminal'       // 4xx — no retry
    | 'retryable'      // 5xx — retry with backoff
    | 'rate-limited';  // 429 — retry after server delay

/** Error Recovery configuration — provided via
 *  customContexts:errorRecovery on the injector chain. */
interface ErrorRecoveryConfig {
    strategy: RetryStrategy;
    circuitBreaker?: CircuitBreakerConfig;
    classifyStatus?: (status: number) =&gt; StatusClassification;
    offlineQueue?: boolean;  // Enable offline queuing (default: true)
}</code></pre>

